Extensive investigation into the optical characteristics of the synthesized PCDs is conducted utilizing UV–Vis and fluorescence spectroscopy, as depicted in Fig. 6 a & b. In the UV–vis spectrum (Fig. 6a), two distinct absorption peaks are prominently visible at 316 nm and 390 nm. These absorption peaks provide valuable insights into the absorption behavior of the PCDs, offering crucial information for understanding their optical properties and potential applications. These peaks correspond to the π-π* transition of the C = C bond and the n-π* transition of the conjugated C = O/C = N bonds, respectively. Interestingly, the emission spectrum slightly exceeds the excitation spectrum, revealing the presence of two peaks. The close proximity of the additional fluorescence excitation peak to the 316 nm absorption peak strongly suggests that this new peak arises from the n-π* transition emission [67,68]. Fig. 6b illustrates the fluorescence excitation and emission spectra. After careful analysis, the optimal excitation wavelength is found to be 475 nm, leading to a maximum emission wavelength of 370 nm. The close proximity of the fluorescence emission peak at 475 nm to the absorption band at 316 nm provides confirmation that the emission is triggered by the n-π* transition associated with conjugated C = O and C = N bonds. This correlation underscores the mechanism behind the fluorescence emission of the synthesized material. Remarkably, the aqueous solution of PCDs displayed blue emissions under the UV chamber at 365 nm excitation. As shown in Fig. 6c, the blue fluorescence of PCDs is reaffirmed by the CIE coordinates at (0.135, 0.216), derived from the fluorescence emission data at 370 nm excitation. This observation confirms the blue fluorescence under UV light at 365 nm. Fluorescence mechanism (Energy-level diagram of PCDs with EDE characteristics.) of PCDs is discussed in Note S2 of the supplementary section (
Fig. S4
). Further, FL spectra of 0.015–0.120 wt% PCDs solution and PVA film and PCDs@PVA NC film when excited at 370 nm are shown in Fig. S5 . The stability of PCDs is evaluated for up to 60 days at room temperature. In comparison to the freshly prepared PCDs solution, a significant retention of normalized PL intensity, approximately 93.12 %, is noted. Furthermore, no significant decrease in PL intensity (Fig. 6d) is observed even after storage for 60 days in dark conditions at room temperature. The corresponding visual photos provided in the inset of Fig. 6d align with the results obtained from the PL spectra, suggesting that PCDs maintained their performance for nearly 60 days without encountering any aggregation or flocculation. The importance of the photostability of PCDs for sensitive fluorescence detection is well recognized. In this study, we investigated the emission characteristics of the PCDs under continuous UV light exposure at 365 nm for a duration of 120 min. As depicted in Fig. 6e, there is no evidence of photobleaching observed in the PCDs, and the fluorescence intensity remained unchanged even after 120 min of uninterrupted UV light exposure. This underscores the remarkable photostability exhibited by the PCDs.

The water-blocking abilities of the PVA NC films are assessed with a WCA analyzer. By adding PCDs, the hydrophobic properties of the PVA film are improved. In particular, the WCA for the pure PVA film is found to be 50°, but this increased to 95° for the composite film containing 0.120 wt% PCDs@PVA (
                           Fig. S8
                        ). The enhancement observed in the WCA of the NC film is likely due to the formation of a dense structure facilitated by intra- and inter-molecular hydrogen bonding between PVA and PCDs. Previously, a comparable finding is documented for PVA films incorporating D-glucose-derived CQDs [100]. The marginal rise in hydrophobicity could be ascribed to the incorporation of functional groups onto the NC film surface. The change in surface chemistry alters the surface energy of the PVA films, rendering them less susceptible to interaction with polar solvents. Consequently, water molecules tend to adopt spherical shapes with minimal contact with the film surface, thereby causing an elevation in the water contact angle. Moreover, PCDs are acknowledged for creating intricate pathways that impede the diffusion of water molecules into the PVA matrix. This reduced water absorption could additionally contribute to effectively maintaining the mechanical properties of the PVA matrices.
